# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: green-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Good atom economy means most of the atoms of the reactants are incorporated in the desired products and only small amounts of unwanted byproducts are formed, reducing the economic and environmental impact of waste disposal.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Atom economy is a different concern than chemical yield, because a high-yielding process can still result in substantial byproducts.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] If the desired product has an enantiomer the reaction needs to be sufficiently stereoselective even when atom economy is 100%.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] A Diels–Alder reaction is an example of a potentially very atom efficient reaction that also can be chemo-, regio-, diastereo- and enantioselective.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Catalytic hydrogenation comes the closest to being an ideal reaction that is extensively practiced both industrially and academically.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Atom economy can also be adjusted if a pendant group is recoverable, for example Evans auxiliary groups.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] However, if this can be avoided it is more desirable, as recovery processes will never be 100%.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Atom economy can be improved upon by careful selection of starting materials and a catalyst system.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Poor atom economy is common in fine chemicals or pharmaceuticals synthesis, and especially in research, where the aim to readily and reliably produce a wide range of complex compounds leads to the use of versatile and dependable, but poorly atom-economical reactions.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] For example, synthesis of an alcohol is readily accomplished by reduction of an ester with lithium aluminium hydride, but the reaction necessarily produces a voluminous floc of aluminum salts, which have to be separated from the product alcohol and disposed of.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] The cost of such hazardous material disposal can be considerable.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] Catalytic hydrogenolysis of an ester is the analogous reaction with a high atom economy, but it requires catalyst optimization, is a much slower reaction and is not applicable universally.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] It is fundamental in chemical reactions of the form A+B→ C+D that two products are necessarily generated though product C may have been the desired one.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] That being the case, D is considered a byproduct.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] As it is a significant goal of green chemistry to maximize the efficiency of the reactants and minimize the production of waste, D must either be found to have use, be eliminated or be as insignificant and innocuous as possible.
[src:green-chemistry/atom-economy] With the new equation of the form A+B→C, the first step in making chemical manufacturing more efficient is the use of reactions that resemble simple addition reactions with the only other additions being catalytic materials.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] A **bio-based material** is a material intentionally made, either wholly or partially, from substances derived from living (or once-living) organisms, such as plants, animals, enzymes, and microorganisms, including bacteria, fungi and yeast.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Due to their main characteristics of being renewable and to their ability to store carbon over their growth, recent years assisted to their upsurge as a valid alternative compared to more traditional materials in view of climate mitigation.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] In European context, more specifically, European Union, which has set 2050 as a target date to reach climate neutrality, is trying to implement, among other measures, the production and utilization of bio-based materials in many diverse sectors.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Indeed, several European regulations, such as the European Industrial Strategy, the EU Biotechnology and Biomanufacturing Initiative and the Circular Action Plan, emphasize bio-materials.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] These regulations aim to support innovation, investment, and market adoption of bio-materials while enhancing the transition towards a circular economy where resources are used more efficiently.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] In this regard, the application of bio-based materials has been already tested on several market segments, ranging from the production of chemicals, to packaging and textiles, till the fabrication of full construction components.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Bio-based materials can differ depending on the origin of the biomass they're mostly constituted.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Moreover, they can be differently manufactured, resulting in either simple or more complex engineered bio-products, which can be used for many applications.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Among processed materials, it is possible to distinguish between bio-based polymers, bio-based plastics, bio-based chemical fibres, bio-based leather, bio-based rubber, bio-based coatings, bio-based material additives, bio-based composites.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Unprocessed materials, instead, may be called biotic material.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Bio-based materials are often biodegradable, but this is not always the case.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] By definition, biodegradable materials are formed or organic compounds which can thus be broken down by living organisms, such as bacteria, fungi, or water molds, and reabsorbed by the natural environment.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Whether a material is biodegradable is determined by its chemical structure, not the origin of the material from which it is made.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Indeed, the sustainability benefits of drop-in biobased plastics occur at the beginning of the material life cycle, but still, when manufactured, their structure is identical to their fossil-based counterparts.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Therefore, these plastics, known as 'drop-ins', are not biodegradable, and should be recycled in existing recycling systems.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] In this regard, biodegradability does not support circularity unless biodegradable materials are recovered and processed by a system that can either recapture or upgrade their value.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Ensuring a proper infrastructure for these materials to remain in the material management system, for instance through industrial composting or anaerobic digestion, is thus considered to be essential.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Similarly, bio-based materials are not necessarily organic, as the term "bio-based" simply indicates the material origin.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] The term "organic" instead refers to the cultivation of plants or the keeping of the animals in compliance with the requirements of the European organic farming standard.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Consequently, a bio-product can be both "bio-based" and "organic," but it is not necessarily so.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] It is not given that bio-based materials always perform better than fossil-based materials.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Their environmental performance depends on a series of factors, related to the sourced material and to the amount and typology of manufacturing processes the raw natural material need to undergo to become a bio-product.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] One of the main factors influencing the sustainability of bio-materials is land consumption, land competition for food production and soil depletion.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] In this regard, in the European context many studies have been conducted to analyze the actual availability of land for the production of bio-materials, while bio-residues and wastes coming from either the agro-industrial and forestry sectors are gaining interest.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Moreover, manufacturing processes needed for the production of competitive bio-alternatives to fossil-based products might lead to higher energy consumptions or to "linear", non-circular, products.
[src:green-chemistry/bio-based-material] Therefore, it is recommended to maintain a critical mindset based on Life Cycle Assessment analysis, as some bio-products could require either extra material or processing to ensure the same quality, resulting necessarily in more energy consumption.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In practice, almost all chemical compounds and materials are subject to biodegradation, the limiting element being time.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Vegetables may degrade within days, whereas some plastics can take a lot of time to degrade.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] A standard for biodegradability used by the European Union is that greater than 90% of the original material must be converted into CO2, water, and minerals by biological processes within 6 months.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradation does not apply to elements, thus heavy metal pollutants do not biodegrade.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The process of biodegradation can be divided into three stages: biodeterioration, biofragmentation, and assimilation.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodeterioration is sometimes described as a surface-level degradation that modifies the mechanical, physical and chemical properties of the material.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] This stage occurs when the material is exposed to abiotic factors in the outdoor environment and allows for further degradation by weakening the material's structure.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Some abiotic factors that influence these initial changes are compression (mechanical), light, temperature and chemicals in the environment.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] While biodeterioration typically occurs as the first stage of biodegradation, it can in some cases be parallel to biofragmentation.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biofragmentation of a polymer is the lytic process in which bonds within a polymer are cleaved, generating oligomers and monomers in its place.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The steps taken to fragment these materials also differ based on the presence of oxygen in the system.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The breakdown of materials by microorganisms when oxygen is present is aerobic digestion, and the breakdown of materials when oxygen is not present is anaerobic digestion.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The main difference between these processes is that anaerobic reactions produce methane, while aerobic reactions do not (however, both reactions produce carbon dioxide, water, some type of residue, and a new biomass).
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In addition, aerobic digestion typically occurs more rapidly than anaerobic digestion, while anaerobic digestion does a better job reducing the volume and mass of the material.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Due to anaerobic digestion's ability to reduce the volume and mass of waste materials and produce a natural gas, anaerobic digestion technology is widely used for waste management systems and as a source of local, renewable energy.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In the assimilation stage, the resulting products from biofragmentation are then integrated into microbial cells.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Some of the products from fragmentation are easily transported within the cell by membrane carriers.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] However, others still have to undergo biotransformation reactions to yield products that can then be transported inside the cell.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Once inside the cell, the products enter catabolic pathways that either lead to the production of adenosine triphosphate (ATP) or elements of the cells structure.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In practice, almost all chemical compounds and materials are subject to biodegradation processes.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The significance, however, is in the relative rates of such processes, such as days, weeks, years or centuries.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] A number of factors determine the rate at which this degradation of organic compounds occurs.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Factors include light, water, oxygen and temperature.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The degradation rate of many organic compounds is limited by their bioavailability, which is the rate at which a substance is absorbed into a system or made available at the site of physiological activity, as compounds must be released into solution before organisms can degrade them.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The rate of biodegradation can be measured in a number of ways.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Respirometry tests can be used for aerobic microbes.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] First one places a solid waste sample in a container with microorganisms and soil, and then aerates the mixture.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Over the course of several days, microorganisms digest the sample bit by bit and produce carbon dioxide – the resulting amount of CO2 serves as an indicator of degradation.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradability can also be measured by anaerobic microbes and the amount of methane or alloy that they are able to produce.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] It's important to note factors that affect biodegradation rates during product testing to ensure that the results produced are accurate and reliable.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Several materials will test as being biodegradable under optimal conditions in a lab for approval but these results may not reflect real world outcomes where factors are more variable.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] For example, a material may have tested as biodegrading at a high rate in the lab may not degrade at a high rate in a landfill because landfills often lack light, water, and microbial activity that are necessary for degradation to occur.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Thus, it is very important that there are standards for plastic biodegradable products, which have a large impact on the environment.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The development and use of accurate standard test methods can help ensure that all plastics that are being produced and commercialized will actually biodegrade in natural environments.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] One test that has been developed for this purpose is DINV 54900.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Recent advances have enabled real-time monitoring of polymer biodegradation using biosensors combined with machine learning, improving the accuracy of degradation assessments under varying environmental conditions.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Polycyclic aromatics are potential cancer-causing compounds that are produced by processing of petroleum and coal.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The term biodegradable plastics refers to materials that maintain their mechanical strength during practical use but break down into low-weight compounds and non-toxic byproducts after their use.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] This breakdown is made possible through an attack of microorganisms on the material, which is typically a non-water-soluble polymer.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Such materials can be obtained through chemical synthesis, fermentation by microorganisms, and from chemically modified natural products.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Plastics biodegrade at highly variable rates.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] PVC-based plumbing is selected for handling sewage because PVC resists biodegradation.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Some packaging materials on the other hand are being developed that would degrade readily upon exposure to the environment.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Examples of synthetic polymers that biodegrade quickly include polycaprolactone, other polyesters and aromatic-aliphatic esters, due to their ester bonds being susceptible to attack by water.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] A prominent example is poly-3-hydroxybutyrate, the renewably derived polylactic acid.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Others are the cellulose-based cellulose acetate and celluloid (cellulose nitrate).
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Under low oxygen conditions plastics break down more slowly.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The breakdown process can be accelerated in specially designed compost heap.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Starch-based plastics will degrade within two to four months in a home compost bin, while polylactic acid is largely undecomposed, requiring higher temperatures.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Polycaprolactone and polycaprolactone-starch composites decompose slower, but the starch content accelerates decomposition by leaving behind a porous, high surface area polycaprolactone.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In 2016, a bacterium named *Ideonella sakaiensis* was found to biodegrade PET.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In 2020, the PET degrading enzyme of the bacterium, PETase, has been genetically modified and combined with MHETase to break down PET faster, and also degrade PEF.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In 2021, researchers reported that a mix of microorganisms from cow stomachs could break down three types of plastics.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Many plastic producers have gone so far even to say that their plastics are compostable, typically listing corn starch as an ingredient.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The term "composting" is often used informally to describe the biodegradation of packaging materials.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Legal definitions exist for compostability, the process that leads to compost.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] **Biodegradability**: the conversion of >90% of the original material into CO2, water and minerals by biological processes within 6 months.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] **Disintegrability**: at least 90% of the original mass should be decomposed into particles that are able to pass through a 2x2 mm sieve.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] **Quality**: absence of toxic substances and other substances that impede composting.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradable technology is established technology with some applications in product packaging, production, and medicine.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The chief barrier to widespread implementation is the trade-off between biodegradability and performance.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] For example, lactide-based plastics are inferior packaging properties in comparison to traditional materials.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradable technology is especially utilized by the bio-medical community.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradable polymers are classified into three groups: medical, ecological, and dual application, while in terms of origin they are divided into two groups: natural and synthetic.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The Clean Technology Group is exploiting the use of supercritical carbon dioxide, which under high pressure at room temperature is a solvent that can use biodegradable plastics to make polymer drug coatings.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The polymer (meaning a material composed of molecules with repeating structural units that form a long chain) is used to encapsulate a drug prior to injection in the body and is based on lactic acid, a compound normally produced in the body, and is thus able to be excreted naturally.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The coating is designed for controlled release over a period of time, reducing the number of injections required and maximizing the therapeutic benefit.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Professor Steve Howdle states that biodegradable polymers are particularly attractive for use in drug delivery, as once introduced into the body they require no retrieval or further manipulation and are degraded into soluble, non-toxic by-products.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Different polymers degrade at different rates within the body and therefore polymer selection can be tailored to achieve desired release rates.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Other biomedical applications include the use of biodegradable, elastic shape-memory polymers.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradable implant materials can now be used for minimally invasive surgical procedures through degradable thermoplastic polymers.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] These polymers are now able to change their shape with increase of temperature, causing shape memory capabilities as well as easily degradable sutures.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] As a result, implants can now fit through small incisions, doctors can easily perform complex deformations, and sutures and other material aides can naturally biodegrade after a completed surgery.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] There is no universal definition for biodegradation and there are various definitions of composting, which has led to much confusion between the terms.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] They are often lumped together; however, they do not have the same meaning.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradation is the naturally occurring breakdown of materials by microorganisms such as bacteria and fungi or other biological activity.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Composting is a human-driven process in which biodegradation occurs under a specific set of circumstances.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The predominant difference between the two is that one process is naturally occurring and one is human-driven.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradable material is capable of decomposing without an oxygen source (anaerobically) into carbon dioxide, water, and biomass, but the timeline is not very specifically defined.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Similarly, compostable material breaks down into carbon dioxide, water, and biomass; however, compostable material also breaks down into inorganic compounds.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The process for composting is more specifically defined, as it is controlled by humans.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Essentially, composting is an accelerated biodegradation process due to optimized circumstances.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Additionally, the end product of composting not only returns to its previous state, but also generates and adds beneficial microorganisms to the soil called humus.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] This organic matter can be used in gardens and on farms to help grow healthier plants in the future.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Composting more consistently occurs within a shorter time frame since it is a more defined process and is expedited by human intervention.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradation can occur in different time frames under different circumstances, but is meant to occur naturally without human intervention.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Even within composting, there are different circumstances under which this can occur.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The two main types of composting are at-home versus commercial.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Both produce healthy soil to be reused – the main difference lies in what materials are able to go into the process.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] At-home composting is mostly used for food scraps and excess garden materials, such as weeds.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Commercial composting is capable of breaking down more complex plant-based products, such as corn-based plastics and larger pieces of material, like tree branches.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Commercial composting begins with a manual breakdown of the materials using a grinder or other machine to initiate the process.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Because at-home composting usually occurs on a smaller scale and does not involve large machinery, these materials would not fully decompose in at-home composting.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Furthermore, one study has compared and contrasted home and industrial composting, concluding that there are advantages and disadvantages to both.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The following studies provide examples in which composting has been defined as a subset of biodegradation in a scientific context.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The first study, "Assessment of Biodegradability of Plastics Under Simulated Composting Conditions in a Laboratory Test Setting," clearly examines composting as a set of circumstances that falls under the category of degradation.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Additionally, this next study looked at the biodegradation and composting effects of chemically and physically crosslinked polylactic acid.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Notably discussing composting and biodegrading as two distinct terms.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The third and final study reviews European standardization of biodegradable and compostable material in the packaging industry, again using the terms separately.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The distinction between these terms is crucial because waste management confusion leads to improper disposal of materials by people on a daily basis.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradation technology has led to massive improvements in how we dispose of waste; there now exist trash, recycling, and compost bins in order to optimize the disposal process.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] However, if these waste streams are commonly and frequently confused, then the disposal process is not at all optimized.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Biodegradable and compostable materials have been developed to ensure more of human waste is able to breakdown and return to its previous state, or in the case of composting even add nutrients to the ground.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] When a compostable product is thrown out as opposed to composted and sent to a landfill, these inventions and efforts are wasted.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Therefore, it is important for citizens to understand the difference between these terms so that materials can be disposed of properly and efficiently.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Plastic pollution from illegal dumping poses health risks to wildlife.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Animals often mistake plastics for food, resulting in intestinal entanglement.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Slow-degrading chemicals, like polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), nonylphenol (NP), and pesticides also found in plastics, can release into environments and subsequently also be ingested by wildlife.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] These chemicals also play a role in human health, as consumption of tainted food (in processes called biomagnification and bioaccumulation) has been linked to issues such as cancers, neurological dysfunction, and hormonal changes.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] A well-known example of biomagnification impacting health in recent times is the increased exposure to dangerously high levels of mercury in fish, which can affect sex hormones in humans.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In efforts to remediate the damages done by slow-degrading plastics, detergents, metals, and other pollutants created by humans, economic costs have become a concern.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Marine litter in particular is notably difficult to quantify and review.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Researchers at the World Trade Institute estimate that cleanup initiatives' cost (specifically in ocean ecosystems) has hit close to thirteen billion dollars a year.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The main concern stems from marine environments, with the biggest cleanup efforts centering around garbage patches in the ocean.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The Great Pacific Garbage Patch, a garbage patch the size of Mexico, is located in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] It is estimated to be upwards of a million square miles in size.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] While the patch contains more obvious examples of litter (plastic bottles, cans, and bags), tiny microplastics are nearly impossible to clean up.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] *National Geographic* reports that even more non-biodegradable materials are finding their way into vulnerable environments – nearly thirty-eight million pieces a year.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Materials that have not degraded can also serve as shelter for invasive species, such as tube worms and barnacles.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] When the ecosystem changes in response to the invasive species, resident species and the natural balance of resources, genetic diversity, and species richness is altered.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] These factors may support local economies in way of hunting and aquaculture, which suffer in response to the change.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Similarly, coastal communities which rely heavily on ecotourism lose revenue thanks to a buildup of pollution, as their beaches or shores are no longer desirable to travelers.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The World Trade Institute also notes that the communities who often feel most of the effects of poor biodegradation are poorer countries without the means to pay for their cleanup.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] In a positive feedback loop effect, they in turn have trouble controlling their own pollution sources.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] The first known use of *biodegradable* in a biological context was in 1959 when it was employed to describe the breakdown of material into innocuous components by microorganisms.
[src:green-chemistry/biodegradation] Now *biodegradable* is commonly associated with environmentally friendly products that are part of the earth's innate cycles like the carbon cycle and capable of decomposing back into natural elements.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The overarching goals of green chemistry—namely, more resource-efficient and inherently safer design of molecules, materials, products, and processes—can be pursued in a wide range of contexts.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Green chemistry evolved and emerged from a variety of existing ideas and research efforts (such as Pollution Prevention, atom economy and catalysis) in the period leading up to the 1990s, in the context of increasing attention to problems of chemical pollution and resource depletion.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The narrower set of concepts later recognized and re-named as green chemistry coalesced in the mid- to late-1990s, along with broader adoption of the new term in the Academic literature (which prevailed over earlier competing terms such as "clean" and "sustainable" chemistry).
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In the United States, the Environmental Protection Agency played a significant supporting role in evolving green chemistry out of its earlier pollution prevention programs, funding, and cooperative coordination with industry.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] At the same time in the United Kingdom, researchers at the University of York, who used the term "clean technology" in the early 1990s, contributed to the establishment of the Green Chemistry Network within the Royal Society of Chemistry, and the launch of the journal *Green Chemistry*.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 1991, in the Netherlands, a special issue called 'green chemistry' [groene chemie] was published in *Chemisch Magazine*.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In the Dutch context, the umbrella term green chemistry was associated with the exploitation of biomass as a renewable feedstock.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 1998, Paul Anastas (who then directed the Green Chemistry Program at the US EPA) and John C.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Warner (then of Polaroid Corporation) published a set of principles to guide the practice of green chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The twelve principles address a range of ways to lower the environmental and health impacts of chemical production, and also indicate research priorities for the development of green chemistry technologies.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Atom economy: Synthetic methods should try to maximize the incorporation of all materials used in the process into the final product.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] This means that less waste will be generated as a result.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Less hazardous chemical syntheses: Synthetic methods should avoid using or generating substances toxic to humans and/or the environment.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Designing safer chemicals: Chemical products should be designed to achieve their desired function while being as non-toxic as possible.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Safer solvents and auxiliaries: Auxiliary substances should be avoided wherever possible, and as non-hazardous as possible when they must be used.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Design for energy efficiency: Energy requirements should be minimized, and processes should be conducted at ambient temperature and pressure whenever possible.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Use of renewable feedstocks: Whenever it is practical to do so, renewable feedstocks or raw materials are preferable to non-renewable ones.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Reduce derivatives: Unnecessary generation of derivatives—such as the use of protecting groups—should be minimized or avoided if possible; such steps require additional reagents and may generate additional waste.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Catalysis: Catalytic reagents that can be used in small quantities to repeat a reaction are superior to stoichiometric reagents (ones that are consumed in a reaction).
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Design for degradation: Chemical products should be designed so that they do not pollute the environment; when their function is complete, they should break down into non-harmful products.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Real-time analysis for pollution prevention: Analytical methodologies need to be further developed to permit real-time, in-process monitoring and control *before* hazardous substances form.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Inherently safer chemistry for accident prevention: Whenever possible, the substances in a process, and the forms of those substances, should be chosen to minimize risks such as explosions, fires, and accidental releases.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Attempts are being made not only to quantify the *greenness* of a chemical process but also to factor in other variables, such as chemical yield, the price of reaction components, safety in handling chemicals, hardware demands, energy profile and ease of product workup and purification.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In one quantitative study, the reduction of nitrobenzene to aniline receives 64 points out of 100 marking it as an acceptable synthesis overall whereas a synthesis of an amide using HMDS is only described as adequate with a combined 32 points.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Green-chemistry methods are applied to the development and manufacture of nanomaterials, with attention to life-cycle impacts and potential nanotoxicity.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The major application of solvents in human activities is in paints and coatings (46% of usage).
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Smaller volume applications include cleaning, de-greasing, adhesives, and in chemical synthesis.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Traditional solvents are often toxic or are chlorinated.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Green solvents, on the other hand, are generally less harmful to health and the environment and preferably more sustainable.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Ideally, solvents would be derived from renewable resources and biodegrade to innocuous, products that occur often in nature.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] However, the manufacture of solvents from biomass can be more harmful to the environment than making the same solvents from fossil fuels.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Thus the environmental impact of solvent manufacture must be considered when a solvent is being selected for a product or process.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Another factor to consider is the fate of the solvent after use.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] If the solvent is being used in an enclosed situation where solvent collection and recycling is feasible, then the energy cost and environmental harm associated with recycling should be considered; in such a situation, water, which is energy-intensive to purify, may not be the greenest choice.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In short, the impact of the entire lifetime of the solvent, from cradle to grave (or cradle to cradle if recycled) must be considered.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] By definition, then, a solvent might be green for one application (because it results in less environmental harm than any other solvent that could be used for that application) and yet not be a green solvent for a different application.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] A classic example is water, which is a very green solvent for consumer products, such as toilet bowl cleaner, but is not a green solvent for the manufacture of polytetrafluoroethylene.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] For the production of that polymer, the use of water as solvent requires the addition of perfluorinated surfactants which are highly persistent.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Instead, supercritical carbon dioxide seems to be the greenest solvent for that application because it performs well without any surfactant.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In summary, no solvent can be declared to be a "green solvent" unless the declaration is limited to a specific application.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Novel or enhanced synthetic techniques can often provide improved environmental performance or enable better adherence to the principles of green chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] For example, the 2005 Nobel Prize for Chemistry was awarded to Yves Chauvin, Robert H.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Some further examples of applied green chemistry are supercritical water oxidation, on water reactions, and dry media reactions.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Bioengineering is also seen as a promising technique for achieving green chemistry goals.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] A number of important process chemicals can be synthesized in engineered organisms, such as shikimate, a Tamiflu precursor which is fermented by Roche in bacteria.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Click chemistry is often cited as a style of chemical synthesis that is consistent with the goals of green chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The concept of 'green pharmacy' has recently been articulated based on similar principles.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 1996, Dow Chemical won the 1996 Greener Reaction Conditions award for their 100% carbon dioxide blowing agent for polystyrene foam production.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Polystyrene foam is a common material used in packing and food transportation.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Seven hundred million pounds are produced each year in the United States alone.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Traditionally, CFC and other ozone-depleting chemicals were used in the production process of the foam sheets, presenting a serious environmental hazard.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Flammable, explosive, and, in some cases toxic hydrocarbons have also been used as CFC replacements, but they present their own problems.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Dow Chemical discovered that supercritical carbon dioxide works equally as well as a blowing agent, without the need for hazardous substances, allowing the polystyrene to be more easily recycled.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The CO2 used in the process is reused from other industries, so the net carbon released from the process is zero.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Addressing the second principle is the peroxide process for producing hydrazine without cogenerating salt.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Hydrazine is traditionally produced by the Olin Raschig process from sodium hypochlorite (the active ingredient in many bleaches) and ammonia.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In the greener peroxide process, hydrogen peroxide is employed as the oxidant and the side product is water.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Addressing the fourth principle, this process does not require auxiliary extracting solvents.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Methyl ethyl ketone is used as a carrier for the hydrazine, the intermediate ketazine phase separates from the reaction mixture, facilitating workup without the need of an extracting solvent.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Addressing the seventh principle is a green route to 1,3-propanediol, which is traditionally generated from petrochemical precursors.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] It can be produced from renewable precursors via the bioseparation of 1,3-propanediol using a genetically modified strain of *E. coli*.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] This diol is used to make new polyesters for the manufacture of carpets.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 2002, Cargill Dow (now NatureWorks) won the Greener Reaction Conditions Award for their improved method for polymerization of polylactic acid.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] However, lactide-base polymers do not perform well and the project was discontinued by Dow in 2005.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Lactic acid is produced by fermenting corn, and then lactide, the cyclic dimer ester of lactic acid, is produced using an efficient, tin-catalyzed cyclization.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The L,L-lactide enantiomer is isolated by distillation and polymerized in the melt to make a crystallizable polymer, which has some applications including textiles and apparel, cutlery, and food packaging.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The NatureWorks PLA process substitutes renewable materials for petroleum feedstocks, doesn't require the use of hazardous organic solvents typical in other PLA processes, and results in a high-quality polymer that is recyclable and compostable.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 2003, Shaw Industries selected a combination of polyolefin resins as the base polymer of choice for EcoWorx due to the low toxicity of its feedstocks, superior adhesion properties, dimensional stability, and its ability to be recycled.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The EcoWorx compound also had to be designed to be compatible with nylon carpet fiber.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Although EcoWorx may be recovered from any fiber type, nylon-6 provides a significant advantage.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Polyolefins are compatible with known nylon-6 depolymerization methods.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Nylon-6 chemistry is well-known and not addressed in first-generation production.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] From its inception, EcoWorx met all of the design criteria necessary to satisfy the needs of the marketplace from a performance, health, and environmental standpoint.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Research indicated that separation of the fiber and backing through elutriation, grinding, and air separation proved to be the best way to recover the face and backing components, but an infrastructure for returning postconsumer EcoWorx to the elutriation process was necessary.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Research also indicated that the postconsumer carpet tile had a positive economic value at the end of its useful life.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] EcoWorx is recognized by MBDC as a certified cradle-to-cradle design.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 2005, Archer Daniels Midland (ADM) and Novozymes won the Greener Synthetic Pathways Award for their enzyme interesterification process.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) mandated labeling of *trans*-fats on nutritional information by January 1, 2006, Novozymes and ADM worked together to develop a clean, enzymatic process for the interesterification of oils and fats by interchanging saturated and unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The result is commercially viable products without *trans*-fats.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In addition to the human health benefits of eliminating *trans*-fats, the process has reduced the use of toxic chemicals and water, prevents vast amounts of byproducts, and reduces the amount of fats and oils wasted.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 2011, the Outstanding Green Chemistry Accomplishments by a Small Business Award went to BioAmber Inc. for integrated production and downstream applications of bio-based succinic acid.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Succinic acid is a platform chemical that is an important starting material in the formulations of everyday products.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Traditionally, succinic acid is produced from petroleum-based feedstocks.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Bio Amber has developed process and technology that produces succinic acid from the fermentation of renewable feedstocks at a lower cost and lower energy expenditure than the petroleum equivalent while sequestering CO2 rather than emitting it.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] However, lower prices of oil precipitated the company into bankruptcy, and bio-sourced succinic acid is now rarely made.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Several laboratory chemicals are controversial from the perspective of Green chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The Massachusetts Institute of Technology created a "Green" Alternatives Wizard to help identify alternatives.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Ethidium bromide, xylene, mercury, and formaldehyde have been identified as "worst offenders" which have alternatives.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Solvents in particular make a large contribution to the environmental impact of chemical manufacturing and there is a growing focus on introducing Greener solvents into the earliest stage of development of these processes: laboratory-scale reaction and purification methods.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In the Pharmaceutical Industry, both GSK and Pfizer have published Solvent Selection Guides for their Drug Discovery chemists.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 2007, The EU put into place the Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals (REACH) program, which requires companies to provide data showing that their products are safe.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] This regulation (1907/2006) ensures not only the assessment of the chemicals' hazards as well as risks during their uses but also includes measures for banning or restricting/authorizing uses of specific substances.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] ECHA, the EU Chemicals Agency in Helsinki, is implementing the regulation, whereas the enforcement lies with the EU member states.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The United States formed the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) in 1970 to protect human and environmental health by creating and enforcing environmental regulation.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Green chemistry builds on the EPA's goals by encouraging chemists and engineers to design chemicals, processes, and products that avoid the creation of toxins and waste.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The U.S. law that governs the majority of industrial chemicals (excluding pesticides, foods, and pharmaceuticals) is the Toxic Substances Control Act (TSCA) of 1976.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Scholars have argued that such market conditions represent a key barrier to the scientific, technical, and commercial success of green chemistry in the U.S., and fundamental policy changes are needed to correct these weaknesses.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Passed in 1990, the Pollution Prevention Act helped foster new approaches for dealing with pollution by preventing environmental problems before they happen.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Green chemistry grew in popularity in the United States after the Pollution Prevention Act of 1990 was passed.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] This Act declared that pollution should be lowered by improving designs and products rather than treatment and disposal.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] These regulations encouraged chemists to reimagine pollution and research ways to limit the toxins in the atmosphere.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 1991, the EPA Office of Pollution Prevention and Toxics created a research grant program encouraging the research and recreation of chemical products and processes to limit the impact on the environment and human health.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The EPA hosts The Green Chemistry Challenge each year to incentivize the economic and environmental benefits of developing and utilizing green chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] In 2008, the State of California approved two laws aiming to encourage green chemistry, launching the California Green Chemistry Initiative.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] One of these statutes required California's Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) to develop new regulations to prioritize "chemicals of concern" and promote the substitution of hazardous chemicals with safer alternatives.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] The resulting regulations took effect in 2013, initiating DTSC's *Safer Consumer Products Program*.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] There are ambiguities in the definition of green chemistry and how it is understood among broader science, policy, and business communities.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Even within chemistry, researchers have used the term "green chemistry" to describe a range of work independently of the framework put forward by Anastas and Warner (i.e., the 12 principles).
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] While not all uses of the term are legitimate (see greenwashing), many are, and the authoritative status of any single definition is uncertain.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] More broadly, the idea of green chemistry can easily be linked (or confused) with related concepts like green engineering, environmental design, or sustainability in general.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Green chemistry's complexity and multifaceted nature makes it difficult to devise clear and simple metrics.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] As a result, "what is green" is often open to debate.
[src:green-chemistry/green-chemistry] Several scientific societies have created awards to encourage research in green chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] An **ionic liquid** (**IL**) is a salt in the liquid state at ambient conditions.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In some contexts, the term has been restricted to salts whose melting point is below a specific temperature, such as 100 °C (212 °F).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] While ordinary liquids such as water and gasoline are predominantly made of electrically neutral molecules, ionic liquids are largely made of ions.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] These substances are variously called **liquid electrolytes**, **ionic melts**, **ionic fluids**, **fused salts**, **liquid salts**, or **ionic glasses**.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Ionic liquids have many potential applications.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They are powerful solvents and can be used as electrolytes.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Salts that are liquid at near-ambient temperature are important for electric battery applications, and have been considered as sealants due to their very low vapor pressure.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Any salt that melts without decomposing or vaporizing usually yields an ionic liquid.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Sodium chloride (NaCl), for example, melts at 801 °C (1,474 °F) into a liquid that consists largely of sodium cations (Na+ ) and chloride anions (Cl− ).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Conversely, when an ionic liquid is cooled, it often forms an ionic solid—which may be either crystalline or glassy.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The ionic bond is usually stronger than the Van der Waals forces between the molecules of ordinary liquids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Because of these strong interactions, salts tend to have high lattice energies, manifested in high melting points.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Some salts, especially those with organic cations, have low lattice energies and thus are liquid at or below room temperature.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Examples include compounds based on the 1-ethyl-3-methylimidazolium (EMIM) cation and include: EMIM:Cl, EMIMAc (acetate anion), EMIM dicyanamide, (C 2H 5)(CH 3)C 3H 3N+ 2·N(CN)− 2, that melts at −21 °C (−6 °F); and 1-butyl-3,5-dimethylpyridinium bromide which becomes a glass below −24 °C (−11 °F).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Low-temperature ionic liquids can be compared to ionic solutions, liquids that contain both ions and neutral molecules, and in particular to the so-called deep eutectic solvents, mixtures of ionic and non-ionic solid substances which have much lower melting points than the pure compounds.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Certain mixtures of nitrate salts can have melting points below 100 °C.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The term "ionic liquid" in the general sense was used as early as 1943.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The discovery date of the "first" ionic liquid is disputed, along with the identity of its discoverer.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Later in 1914, Paul Walden reported one of the first stable room-temperature ionic liquids ethylammonium nitrate (C 2H 5)NH+ 3·NO− 3 (m.p.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In the 1970s and 1980s, ionic liquids based on alkyl-substituted imidazolium and pyridinium cations, with halide or tetrahalogenoaluminate anions, were developed as potential electrolytes in batteries.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] For the imidazolium halogenoaluminate salts, their physical properties—such as viscosity, melting point, and acidity—could be adjusted by changing the alkyl substituents and the imidazolium/pyridinium and halide/halogenoaluminate ratios.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Two major drawbacks for some applications were moisture sensitivity and acidity or basicity.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In 1992, Wilkes and Zawarotko obtained ionic liquids with 'neutral' weakly coordinating anions such as hexafluorophosphate (PF− 6) and tetrafluoroborate (BF− 4), allowing a much wider range of applications.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs are typically colorless viscous liquids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They are often moderate to poor conductors of electricity, and rarely self-ionize.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They do, however, have a very large electrochemical window, enabling electrochemical refinement of otherwise intractable ores.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They exhibit low vapor pressure, which can be as low as 10−10 Pa.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Many have low combustibility and are thermally stable.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The solubility properties of ILs are diverse.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Saturated aliphatic compounds are generally only sparingly soluble in ionic liquids, whereas alkenes show somewhat greater solubility, and aldehydes often completely miscible.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Solubility differences can be exploited in biphasic catalysis, such as hydrogenation and hydrocarbonylation processes, allowing for relatively easy separation of products and/or unreacted substrate(s).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Gas solubility follows the same trend, with carbon dioxide gas showing good solubility in many ionic liquids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Carbon monoxide is less soluble in ionic liquids than in many popular organic solvents, and hydrogen is only slightly soluble (similar to the solubility in water) and may vary relatively little between the more common ionic liquids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The miscibility of ionic liquids with water or organic solvents varies with side chain lengths on the cation and with choice of anion.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They can be functionalized to act as acids, bases, or ligands, and are precursors salts in the preparation of stable carbenes.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Because of their distinctive properties, ionic liquids have been investigated for many applications.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Some ionic liquids can be distilled under vacuum conditions at temperatures near 300 °C.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The vapor is not made up of separated ions, but consists of ion pairs.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Some ILs do not freeze down to very low temperatures (even −150 °C), The glass transition temperature was detected below −100 °C in the case of N-methyl-N-alkylpyrrolidinium cations fluorosulfonyl-trifluoromethanesulfonylimide (FTFSI).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Low-temperature ionic liquids (below 130 K) have been proposed as the fluid base for an extremely large diameter spinning liquid-mirror telescope to be based on the Moon.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Water is a common impurity in ionic liquids, as it can be absorbed from the atmosphere and influences the transport properties of RTILs, even at relatively low concentrations.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Classically, ILs consist of salts of unsymmetrical, flexible organic cations with symmetrical weakly coordinating anions.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Both cationic and anionic components have been widely varied.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Room-temperature ionic liquids (RTILs) are dominated by salts derived from 1-methylimidazole, i.e., 1-alkyl-3-methylimidazolium.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Other imidazolium cations are 1-butyl-2,3-dimethylimidazolium (BMMIM or DBMIM) and 1,3-di(*N*,*N*-dimethylaminoethyl)-2-methylimidazolium (DAMI).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Other *N*-heterocyclic cations are derived from pyridine: 4-methyl-*N*-butyl-pyridinium (MBPy) and *N*-octylpyridinium (C8Py).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Conventional quaternary ammonium cations also form ILs, e.g. tetraethylammonium (TEA) and tetrabutylammonium (TBA).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Typical anions in ionic liquids include the following: tetrafluoroborate (BF4), hexafluorophosphate (PF6), bis-trifluoromethanesulfonimide (NTf2), trifluoromethanesulfonate (OTf), dicyanamide (N(CN)2), hydrogensulfate (HSO−4), and ethyl sulfate (EtOSO3).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Magnetic ionic liquids can be synthesized by incorporating paramagnetic anions, illustrated by 1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium tetrachloroferrate.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Protic ionic liquids are formed via a proton transfer from an acid to a base.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In contrast to other ionic liquids, which generally are formed through a sequence of synthesis steps, protic ionic liquids can be created more easily by simply mixing the acid and base.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Phosphonium cations (R4P+) are less common but offer some advantageous properties.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Some examples of phosphonium cations are trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium (P6,6,6,14) and tributyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium (P4,4,4,14).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Polymerized ionic liquids, poly(ionic liquid)s or polymeric ionic liquids, all abbreviated as PIL is the polymeric form of ionic liquids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They have half of the ionicity of ionic liquids since one ion is fixed as the polymer moiety to form a polymeric chain.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] PILs have a similar range of applications, comparable with those of ionic liquids but the polymer architecture provides a better chance for controlling the ionic conductivity.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] They have extended the applications of ionic liquids for designing smart materials or solid electrolytes.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Many applications have been considered, but few have been commercialized.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs are used in the production of gasoline by catalyzing alkylation.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] An IL based on tetraalkylphosphonium iodide is a solvent for tributyltin iodide, which functions as a catalyst to rearrange the monoepoxide of butadiene.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] This process was commercialized as a route to 2,5-dihydrofuran, but later discontinued.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs improve the catalytic performance of palladium nanoparticles.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Furthermore, ionic liquids can be used as pre-catalysts for chemical transformations.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In this regard dialkylimidazoliums such as [EMIM]Ac have been used in the combination with a base to generate *N*-heterocyclic carbenes (NHCs).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] These imidazolium based NHCs are known to catalyse a number transformations such as the benzoin condensation and the OTHO reaction.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Recognizing that approximately 50% of commercial pharmaceuticals are salts, ionic liquid forms of a number of pharmaceuticals have been investigated.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Combining a pharmaceutically active cation with a pharmaceutically active anion leads to a Dual Active ionic liquid in which the actions of two drugs are combined.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs can extract specific compounds from plants for pharmaceutical, nutritional and cosmetic applications, such as the antimalarial drug artemisinin from the plant *Artemisia annua*.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The dissolution of cellulose by ILs has attracted interest.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] A patent application from 1930 showed that 1-alkylpyridinium chlorides dissolve cellulose.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Following in the footsteps of the lyocell process, which uses hydrated N-methylmorpholine N-oxide as a solvent for pulp and paper.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The "valorization" of cellulose, i.e. its conversion to more valuable chemicals, has been achieved by the use of ionic liquids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Representative products are glucose esters, sorbitol, and alkylgycosides.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] IL 1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium chloride dissolves freeze-dried banana pulp and with an additional 15% dimethyl sulfoxide, lends itself to carbon-13 NMR analysis.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In this way the entire complex of starch, sucrose, glucose, and fructose can be monitored as a function of banana ripening.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Beyond cellulose, ILs have also shown potential in the dissolution, extraction, purification, processing and modification of other biopolymers such as chitin/chitosan, starch, alginate, collagen, gelatin, keratin, and fibroin.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] For example, ILs allow for the preparation of biopolymer materials in different forms (e.g. sponges, films, microparticles, nanoparticles, and aerogels) and better biopolymer chemical reactions, leading to biopolymer-based drug/gene-delivery carriers.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Moreover, ILs enable the synthesis of chemically modified starches with high efficiency and degrees of substitution (DS) and the development of various starch-based materials such as thermoplastic starch, composite films, solid polymer electrolytes, nanoparticles and drug carriers.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] The IL 1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium chloride has been investigated for the recovery of uranium and other metals from spent nuclear fuel and other sources.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs are potential heat transfer and storage media in solar thermal energy systems.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Concentrating solar thermal facilities such as parabolic troughs and solar power towers focus the sun's energy onto a receiver, which can generate temperatures of around 600 °C (1,112 °F).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] This heat can then generate electricity in a steam or other cycle.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] For buffering during cloudy periods or to enable generation overnight, energy can be stored by heating an intermediate fluid.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Although nitrate salts have been the medium of choice since the early 1980s, they freeze at 220 °C (428 °F) and thus require heating to prevent solidification.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Ionic liquids such as [C4mim][BF 4] have more favorable liquid-phase temperature ranges (−75 to 459 °C) and could therefore be excellent liquid thermal storage media and heat transfer fluids.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Ionic liquids have been investigated as solvents and reaction media for recycling processes, including polymer recycling and metal recovery.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] In polymer recycling, ionic liquids can support selective dissolution and purification steps in solvent-based recycling, and they have also been explored as media that influence depolymerization pathways for some condensation polymers (e.g., polyamides and polyesters).
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] For practical implementation, efficient recovery and reuse of the ionic liquid is generally considered important due to cost and sustainability considerations.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs can replace water as the electrolyte in metal-air batteries.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs are attractive because of their low vapor pressure.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Furthermore, ILs have an electrochemical window of up to six volts (versus 1.23 for water) supporting more energy-dense metals.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Energy densities from 900 to 1600 watt-hours per kilogram appear possible.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs can act as dispersing agents in paints to enhance finish, appearance, and drying properties.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs are used for dispersing nanomaterials at IOLITEC.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] ILs and amines have been investigated for capturing carbon dioxide CO 2 and purifying natural gas.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Some ionic liquids have been shown to reduce friction and wear in basic tribological testing, and their polar nature makes them candidate lubricants for tribotronic applications.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] While the comparatively high cost of ionic liquids currently prevents their use as neat lubricants, adding ionic liquids in concentrations as low as 0.5 wt% may significantly alter the lubricating performance of conventional base oils.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Thus, the current focus of research is on using ionic liquids as additives to lubricating oils, often with the motivation to replace widely used, ecologically harmful lubricant additives.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] However, the claimed ecological advantage of ionic liquids has been questioned repeatedly and is yet to be demonstrated from a life-cycle perspective.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Ionic liquids' low volatility effectively eliminates a major pathway for environmental release and contamination.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Ionic liquids' aquatic toxicity is as severe as or more so than many current solvents.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Ultrasound can degrade solutions of imidazolium-based ionic liquids with hydrogen peroxide and acetic acid to relatively innocuous compounds.
[src:green-chemistry/ionic-liquid] Despite low vapor pressure many ionic liquids are combustible.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A **solvent** (from the Latin *solvō*, "loosen, untie, solve") is a substance that dissolves a solute, resulting in a solution.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A solvent is usually a liquid but can also be a solid, a gas, or a supercritical fluid.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Water is a solvent for polar molecules, and the most common solvent used by living things; all the ions and proteins in a cell are dissolved in water within the cell.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Major uses of solvents are in paints, paint removers, inks, and dry cleaning.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvents find various applications in chemical, pharmaceutical, oil, and gas industries, including in chemical syntheses and purification processes.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Some petrochemical solvents are highly toxic and emit volatile organic compounds.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Biobased solvents are usually more expensive, but ideally less toxic and biodegradable.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Biogenic raw materials usable for solvent production are for example lignocellulose, starch and sucrose, but also waste and byproducts from other industries (such as terpenes, vegetable oils and animal fats).
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] When one substance is dissolved into another, a solution is formed.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This is opposed to the situation when the compounds are insoluble like sand in water.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] In a solution, all of the ingredients are uniformly distributed at a molecular level and no residue remains.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A solvent-solute mixture consists of a single phase with all solute molecules occurring as *solvates* (solvent-solute complexes), as opposed to separate continuous phases as in suspensions, emulsions and other types of non-solution mixtures.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The ability of one compound to be dissolved in another is known as solubility; if this occurs in all proportions, it is called miscible.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] In addition to mixing, the substances in a solution interact with each other at the molecular level.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] When something is dissolved, molecules of the solvent arrange around molecules of the solute.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Heat transfer is involved and entropy is increased making the solution more thermodynamically stable than the solute and solvent separately.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This arrangement is mediated by the respective chemical properties of the solvent and solute, such as hydrogen bonding, dipole moment and polarizability.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvation does not cause a chemical reaction or chemical configuration changes in the solute.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] However, solvation resembles a coordination complex formation reaction, often with considerable energetics (heat of solvation and entropy of solvation) and is thus far from a neutral process.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] When one substance dissolves into another, a solution is formed.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A solution is a homogeneous mixture consisting of a solute dissolved into a solvent.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The solute is the substance that is being dissolved, while the solvent is the dissolving medium.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solutions can be formed with many different types and forms of solutes and solvents.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvents can be broadly classified into two categories: *polar* and *non-polar*.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A special case is elemental mercury, whose solutions are known as amalgams; also, other metal solutions exist which are liquid at room temperature.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Generally, the dielectric constant of the solvent provides a rough measure of a solvent's polarity.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The strong polarity of water is indicated by its high dielectric constant of 88 (at 0 °C).
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvents with a dielectric constant of less than 15 are generally considered to be nonpolar.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The dielectric constant measures the solvent's tendency to partly cancel the field strength of the electric field of a charged particle immersed in it.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This reduction is then compared to the field strength of the charged particle in a vacuum.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Heuristically, the dielectric constant of a solvent can be thought of as its ability to reduce the solute's effective internal charge.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Generally, the dielectric constant of a solvent is an acceptable predictor of the solvent's ability to dissolve common ionic compounds, such as salts.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Dielectric constants are not the only measure of polarity.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Because solvents are used by chemists to carry out chemical reactions or observe chemical and biological phenomena, more specific measures of polarity are required.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Most of these measures are sensitive to chemical structure.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The *Grunwald–Winstein m**Y** scale* measures polarity in terms of solvent influence on buildup of positive charge of a solute during a chemical reaction.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The *Hildebrand parameter* is the square root of **cohesive energy density**.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] It can be used with nonpolar compounds, but cannot accommodate complex chemistry.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Reichardt's dye, a solvatochromic dye that changes color in response to polarity, gives a scale of *ET*(30) values.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] *ET* is the transition energy between the ground state and the lowest excited state in kcal/mol, and (30) identifies the dye.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Another, roughly correlated scale (*ET*(33)) can be defined with Nile red.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Gregory's solvent ϸ parameter is a quantum chemically derived charge density parameter.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This parameter seems to reproduce many of the experimental solvent parameters (especially the donor and acceptor numbers) using this charge decomposition analysis approach, with an electrostatic basis.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The ϸ parameter was originally developed to quantify and explain the Hofmeister series by quantifying polyatomic ions and the monatomic ions in a united manner.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The polarity, dipole moment, polarizability and hydrogen bonding of a solvent determines what type of compounds it is able to dissolve and with what other solvents or liquid compounds it is miscible.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Generally, polar solvents dissolve polar compounds best and non-polar solvents dissolve non-polar compounds best; hence "*like dissolves like*".
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Strongly polar compounds like sugars (e.g. sucrose) or ionic compounds, like inorganic salts (e.g. table salt) dissolve only in very polar solvents like water, while strongly non-polar compounds like oils or waxes dissolve only in very non-polar organic solvents like hexane.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Similarly, water and hexane (or vinegar and vegetable oil) are not miscible with each other and will quickly separate into two layers even after being shaken well.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Polarity can be separated to different contributions.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] For example, the **Kamlet-Taft parameters** are dipolarity/polarizability (*π**), hydrogen-bonding acidity (*α*) and hydrogen-bonding basicity (*β*).
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] These can be calculated from the wavelength shifts of 3–6 different solvatochromic dyes in the solvent, usually including Reichardt's dye, nitroaniline and diethylnitroaniline.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Another option, Hansen solubility parameters, separates the cohesive energy density into dispersion, polar, and hydrogen bonding contributions.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvents with a dielectric constant (more accurately, relative static permittivity) greater than 15 (i.e. polar or polarizable) can be further divided into protic and aprotic.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Protic solvents, such as water, solvate anions (negatively charged solutes) strongly via hydrogen bonding.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Polar aprotic solvents, such as acetone or dichloromethane, tend to have large dipole moments (separation of partial positive and partial negative charges within the same molecule) and solvate positively charged species via their negative dipole.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] In chemical reactions the use of polar protic solvents favors the SN1 reaction mechanism, while polar aprotic solvents favor the SN2 reaction mechanism.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] These polar solvents are capable of forming hydrogen bonds with water to dissolve in water whereas non-polar solvents are not capable of strong hydrogen bonds.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The solvents are grouped into nonpolar, polar aprotic, and polar protic solvents, with each group ordered by increasing polarity.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The properties of solvents which exceed those of water are bolded.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The ACS Green Chemistry Institute maintains a tool for the selection of solvents based on a principal component analysis of solvent properties.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The Hansen solubility parameter (HSP) values are based on dispersion bonds (δD), polar bonds (δP) and hydrogen bonds (δH).
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] These contain information about the inter-molecular interactions with other solvents and also with polymers, pigments, nanoparticles, etc.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This allows for rational formulations knowing, for example, that there is a good HSP match between a solvent and a polymer.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Rational substitutions can also be made for "good" solvents (effective at dissolving the solute) that are "bad" (expensive or hazardous to health or the environment).
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The following table shows that the intuitions from "non-polar", "polar aprotic" and "polar protic" are put numerically – the "polar" molecules have higher levels of δP and the protic solvents have higher levels of δH.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Because numerical values are used, comparisons can be made rationally by comparing numbers.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] For example, acetonitrile is much more polar than acetone but exhibits slightly less hydrogen bonding.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] If, for environmental or other reasons, a solvent or solvent blend is required to replace another of equivalent solvency, the substitution can be made on the basis of the Hansen solubility parameters of each.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The values for mixtures are taken as the weighted averages of the values for the neat solvents.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This can be calculated by trial-and-error, a spreadsheet of values, or HSP software.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A 1:1 mixture of toluene and 1,4 dioxane has δD, δP and δH values of 17.8, 1.6 and 5.5, comparable to those of chloroform at 17.8, 3.1 and 5.7 respectively.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Because of the health hazards associated with toluene itself, other mixtures of solvents may be found using a full HSP dataset.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The boiling point is an important property because it determines the speed of evaporation.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Small amounts of low-boiling-point solvents like diethyl ether, dichloromethane, or acetone will evaporate in seconds at room temperature, while high-boiling-point solvents like water or dimethyl sulfoxide need higher temperatures, an air flow, or the application of vacuum for fast evaporation.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Most organic solvents have a lower density than water, which means they are lighter than and will form a layer on top of water.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Important exceptions are most of the halogenated solvents like dichloromethane or chloroform will sink to the bottom of a container, leaving water as the top layer.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This is crucial to remember when partitioning compounds between solvents and water in a separatory funnel during chemical syntheses.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Often, specific gravity is cited in place of density.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Specific gravity is defined as the density of the solvent divided by the density of water at the same temperature.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] As such, specific gravity is a unitless value.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] It readily communicates whether a water-insoluble solvent will float (SG < 1.0) or sink (SG > 1.0) when mixed with water.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Multicomponent solvents appeared after World War II in the USSR, and continue to be used and produced in the post-Soviet states.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] These solvents may have one or more applications, but they are not universal preparations.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Most organic solvents are flammable or highly flammable, depending on their volatility.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Exceptions are some chlorinated solvents like dichloromethane and chloroform.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Mixtures of solvent vapors and air can explode.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvent vapors are heavier than air; they will sink to the bottom and can travel large distances nearly undiluted.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvent vapors can also be found in supposedly empty drums and cans, posing a flash fire hazard; hence empty containers of volatile solvents should be stored open and upside down.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Both diethyl ether and carbon disulfide have exceptionally low autoignition temperatures which increase greatly the fire risk associated with these solvents.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The autoignition temperature of carbon disulfide is below 100 °C (212 °F), so objects such as steam pipes, light bulbs, hotplates, and recently extinguished bunsen burners are able to ignite its vapors.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] In addition some solvents, such as methanol, can burn with a very hot flame which can be nearly invisible under some lighting conditions.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] This can delay or prevent the timely recognition of a dangerous fire, until flames spread to other materials.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Ethers like diethyl ether and tetrahydrofuran (THF) can form highly explosive organic peroxides upon exposure to oxygen and light.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] THF is normally more likely to form such peroxides than diethyl ether.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] One of the most susceptible solvents is diisopropyl ether, but all ethers are considered to be potential peroxide sources.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The heteroatom (oxygen) stabilizes the formation of a free radical which is formed by the abstraction of a hydrogen atom by another free radical.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The carbon-centered free radical thus formed is able to react with an oxygen molecule to form a peroxide compound.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The process of peroxide formation is greatly accelerated by exposure to even low levels of light, but can proceed slowly even in dark conditions.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Unless a desiccant is used which can destroy the peroxides, they will concentrate during distillation, due to their higher boiling point.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] When sufficient peroxides have formed, they can form a crystalline, shock-sensitive solid precipitate at the mouth of a container or bottle.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Minor mechanical disturbances, such as scraping the inside of a vessel, the dislodging of a deposit, or merely twisting the cap may provide sufficient energy for the peroxide to detonate or explode violently.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Peroxide formation is not a significant problem when fresh solvents are used up quickly; they are more of a problem in laboratories which may take years to finish a single bottle.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Low-volume users should acquire only small amounts of peroxide-prone solvents, and dispose of old solvents on a regular periodic schedule.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] To avoid explosive peroxide formation, ethers should be stored in an airtight container, away from light, because both light and air can encourage peroxide formation.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A number of tests can be used to detect the presence of a peroxide in an ether; one is to use a combination of iron(II) sulfate and potassium thiocyanate.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The peroxide is able to oxidize the Fe2+ ion to an Fe3+ ion, which then forms a deep-red coordination complex with the thiocyanate.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Peroxides may be removed by washing with acidic iron(II) sulfate, filtering through alumina, or distilling from sodium/benzophenone.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Alumina degrades the peroxides but some could remain intact in it, therefore it must be disposed of properly.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The advantage of using sodium/benzophenone is that moisture and oxygen are removed as well.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] General health hazards associated with solvent exposure include toxicity to the nervous system, reproductive damage, liver and kidney damage, respiratory impairment, cancer, hearing loss, and dermatitis.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Many solvents can lead to a sudden loss of consciousness if inhaled in large amounts.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Solvents like diethyl ether and chloroform have been used in medicine as anesthetics, sedatives, and hypnotics for a long time.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Many solvents (e.g. from gasoline or solvent-based glues) are abused recreationally in glue sniffing, often with harmful long-term health effects such as neurotoxicity or cancer.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Fraudulent substitution of 1,5-pentanediol by the psychoactive 1,4-butanediol by a subcontractor caused the Bindeez product recall.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Ethanol (grain alcohol) is a widely used and abused psychoactive drug.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] If ingested, the so-called "toxic alcohols" (other than ethanol) such as methanol, 1-propanol, and ethylene glycol metabolize into toxic aldehydes and acids, which cause potentially fatal metabolic acidosis.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The commonly available alcohol solvent methanol can cause permanent blindness or death if ingested.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The solvent 2-butoxyethanol, used in fracking fluids, can cause hypotension and metabolic acidosis.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Chronic solvent exposures are often caused by the inhalation of solvent vapors, or the ingestion of diluted solvents, repeated over the course of an extended period.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Some solvents can damage internal organs like the liver, the kidneys, the nervous system, or the brain.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] The cumulative brain effects of long-term or repeated exposure to some solvents is called chronic solvent-induced encephalopathy (CSE).
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Chronic exposure to organic solvents in the work environment can produce a range of adverse neuropsychiatric effects.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] For example, occupational exposure to organic solvents has been associated with higher numbers of painters suffering from alcoholism.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Ethanol has a synergistic effect when taken in combination with many solvents; for instance, a combination of toluene/benzene and ethanol causes greater nausea/vomiting than either substance alone.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Some organic solvents are known or suspected to be cataractogenic.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A mixture of aromatic hydrocarbons, aliphatic hydrocarbons, alcohols, esters, ketones, and terpenes were found to greatly increase the risk of developing cataracts in the lens of the eye.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] A major pathway of induced health effects arises from spills or leaks of solvents, especially chlorinated solvents, that reach the underlying soil.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Since solvents readily migrate substantial distances, the creation of widespread soil contamination is not uncommon; this is particularly a health risk if aquifers are affected.
[src:green-chemistry/solvent] Vapor intrusion can occur from sites with extensive subsurface solvent contamination.
